<!-- Principle 1 -->
<section class="section" style="background-color: #F0F0F0;">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="two-col">
      <div style="position: sticky; top: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 5rem; color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem; transform: rotate(-3deg);">01.</h2>
        <h3 style="font-size: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Breaking the Grid</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #FF0000;">"You must know the grid to break it"</p>
      </div>
      
      <div>
        <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          The grid system was the foundation of Swiss typography—a mathematical framework ensuring perfect alignment. Swiss Punk acknowledged this foundation, then <span style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 0 4px;">deliberately broke it</span>.
        </p>
        
        <div style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 1.5rem; border: 4px solid #000; margin: 2rem 0;">
          <h4 style="font-size: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">What This Means:</h4>
          <ul style="list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8; font-size: 1.125rem;">
            <li><strong>Asymmetric layouts</strong> - Not random, but intentional disruption</li>
            <li><strong>Overlapping elements</strong> - Text refuses to stay in columns</li>
            <li><strong>Diagonal alignments</strong> - Breaking horizontal tyranny</li>
            <li><strong>Irregular spacing</strong> - Intuition over mathematics</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 2 -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="two-col">
      <div style="position: sticky; top: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 5rem; color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 1rem; transform: rotate(2deg);">02.</h2>
        <h3 style="font-size: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Typography as Expression</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0000FF;">"Type is the hero, not invisible"</p>
      </div>
      
      <div>
        <p style="font-size: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          Swiss Punk rejected the idea that typography should be invisible. Instead, it made typography the <strong>star</strong> of the design.
        </p>
        
        <div class="card" style="background: #fff; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          <h5 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Mixed Typefaces & Weights</h5>
          <p>Combining different fonts—even within single words—to create texture and emphasis.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card" style="background: #0000FF; color: #fff; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          <h5 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Diagonal & Rotated Type</h5>
          <p>Text set at angles, creating dynamic movement. Typically 3-15 degrees.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card" style="background: #fff; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          <h5 style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 900; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Stair-Stepped Layouts</h5>
          <p>Text arranged in steps, each word offset vertically. A signature Weingart technique.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 3 -->
<section class="section" style="background-color: #000; color: #fff;">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: 5rem; color: #FFFF00; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 2rem; transform: rotate(-2deg);">03. Layered Composition</h2>
    
    <div class="three-col" style="margin-top: 3rem;">
      <div style="background: #fff; color: #000; padding: 2rem; transform: rotate(-2deg);">
        <h4 style="color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem;">Transparent Overlays</h4>
        <p>Text layered on text, shapes on shapes, creating depth and visual complexity.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div style="background: #FF0000; color: #fff; padding: 2rem; transform: rotate(1deg);">
        <h4 style="margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem;">Halftone Patterns</h4>
        <p>Using photographic screens as texture, creating grainy surfaces that contrast with sharp type.</p>
      </div>
      
      <div style="background: #fff; color: #000; padding: 2rem; transform: rotate(-1deg);">
        <h4 style="color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size: 1.5rem;">Geometric Shapes</h4>
        <p>Circles, squares, triangles used as structural elements that interact with type.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 4 -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="two-col">
      <div style="position: sticky; top: 2rem;">
        <h2 style="font-size: 5rem; color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem; transform: rotate(3deg);">04.</h2>
        <h3 style="font-size: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Kinetic Energy</h3>
        <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #FF0000;">"Motion in static design"</p>
      </div>
      
      <div>
        <div style="background: #FFFF00; padding: 2rem; border: 4px solid #000; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
          <p style="font-size: 1.75rem; font-weight: 700; line-height: 1.3;">
            Swiss Style was STATIC.<br>
            Swiss Punk is <span style="color: #FF0000;">DYNAMIC</span>.
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
          Even though Swiss Punk designs are printed on paper, they feel like they're <strong>moving</strong>. This kinetic quality comes from:
        </p>
        
        <ul style="list-style-type: square; padding-left: 1.5rem; font-size: 1.125rem; line-height: 2;">
          <li><strong>Angular compositions</strong> that suggest motion</li>
          <li><strong>Diagonal elements</strong> that create visual tension</li>
          <li><strong>Layered transparency</strong> implying depth</li>
          <li><strong>Varied scales</strong> creating push-pull dynamics</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- Principle 5 -->
<section class="section" style="background-color: #F0F0F0;">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 style="font-size: 4rem; color: #0000FF; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 3rem; transform: rotate(-2deg);">
      05. Intuition = Analysis
    </h2>
    
    <div style="max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <p style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 700; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        The most revolutionary principle of all
      </p>
      
      <div class="two-col">
        <div>
          <h3 style="font-size: 1.5rem; color: #FF0000; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Swiss Style Said:</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 1.25rem;">Design must be <strong>rational</strong>, <strong>objective</strong>, and <strong>analytical</strong>. Remove emotion. Follow the system.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div>
          <h3 style="font-size: 1.5rem; color: #0000FF; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Swiss Punk Said:</h3>
          <p style="font-size: 1.25rem;">Design requires <strong>both</strong> analytical thinking <strong>and</strong> intuitive feeling. Trust your gut. Experiment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div style="background: #fff; padding: 3rem; border: 8px solid #000; box-shadow: 12px 12px 0 #000; margin-top: 3rem; transform: rotate(-1deg);">
        <div style="transform: rotate(1deg); text-align: center;">
          <p style="font-size: 2rem; font-style: italic; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
            "How many different ways can I see this same old stuff?"
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; color: #FF0000;">— Wolfgang Weingart</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

